    "dtime": 4293000,
    "ptime": 4293000,
    "author": "Dirk Trossen",
    "text": "@DirkK this brings me back to your \"Is it QoS on steroids?\" question. My comment here would be that it will depend on what 'quality' here is, which in QoS work is usually limited to the packet delivery characteristics (loss, BW, latency). But what if the 'way' the delivery is done is meant to change according to the semantics of the application? In the recent draft to the RTG WG, we captured this as 'routing beyond reachability'. So it's not really about 'quality' but 'purpose'.<br/>"
  },
  {
    "dtime": 4350000,
    "ptime": 4350000,
    "author": "Adrian Farrel",
    "text": "@Nik \"convergence\" depends on the routing algorithm in use. But if you consider that the routing algorithm (centralised or distributed) needs to have a consistent view of the state of the network, then there is some element of convergence. In a centralised system, you need to \"converge\" reports on the state of the network to the central node (by whatever means - NBI has been proposed, listening to routing protocols has been proposed, hybrids using an NBI from a routing node also)<br/>"
  },
